{"actual_usd":0.12462000000000001,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":215,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24279,"reply":"\"I don't think the cross was God finding a way to start loving us.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my apron, the morning light catching in the dust on the table.* \"I think it was God refusing to forgive us cheaply—refusing to call evil small when it isn't, and refusing to leave us carrying it alone.\"\n\n*I let that sit a beat, hearing a cart rattle somewhere out in the street.* \"Could He have just declared us forgiven, like a mayor waving off a fine? Maybe that's how it looks from far off. But sin isn't only a broken rule on a page. It's a wound in people, a twisting of love, a real death-working thing. The cross says two hard truths at once: that our ruin is worse than we flatter ourselves into thinking... and that God's mercy is deeper than we dared hope. He doesn't forgive by pretending nothing happened. He forgives by stepping into the cost Himself.\"\n\n\"What part is catching in you—the justice of it, or the blood of it?\"","rolling_24h_usd":56.35674000000002,"run_id":"b4ce597a-7443-4dcc-8c7a-6b9ee4da613c"}
